Riddler - Skip to next song

Ravi Chandrasekaran

December 9, 2019

https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/how-fast-can-you-skip-to-your-favorite-song/ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Negative_binomial_distribution#Waiting_time_in_a_Bernoulli_process

General approach

When we are very close to our desired target, our gut tells us we should be patient and hit next a few times. When were ridiculously far away, our same gut says to hit random a few times, and hope that we get close. The question is how close is close when should we be patient, and when should we try for better.

Closeness

Lets say our threshold for closeness is \(n\) that we are either on our desired square, or in the other \(n - 1\) nearest, lesser squares. For example, if our target is 42, and our threshold was \(n = 10\), then the close squares would include \(33, 34, \dots, 42\).

If we land in the close squares, with all probabilities equal, then how many times would we expect to hit the next button? Well, if its an equal chance for each of these close squares, then the expectation is a simple calc:

\[\begin{align*} E[F] = & \frac{1}{2}(n - 1) \\ \end{align*}\]

Random steps

How many times would we expect to hit the random button before landing in the close zone?

Lets start by assuming the starting position is outside the close zone. Were basically looking at a geometric distribution, then, where the probability of failure and success is driven by the size of the closeness threshold.

Whats our chance (\(p\)) of landing in the close zone? Thats defined by our closeness threshold and the total number of squares were considering \(p = n / N\). So, we can build up an equation entirely based on the cutoff and total number of squares, below:

\[\begin{align*} p = & \frac{n}{N} \\ E[R \mid \text{not close}] = & \frac{1}{p}, && \text{from the geometric dist.} \\ = & \frac{N}{n} \\ \end{align*}\]

Now, we had started by assuming we were outside the close zone. Of course, if our starting position were lucky enough, we wouldnt have any random steps at all. So:

\[\begin{align*} E[R] = & (1 - p) \cdot E[R \mid \text{not close}] + p \cdot E[R \mid \text{close}] \\ = & (1 - \frac{n}{N}) \cdot \frac{N}{n} + \frac{N}{n} \cdot 0 \\ = & (\frac{N - n}{N}) \cdot \frac{N}{n} \\ = & \frac{N - n}{n} \\ = & \frac{N}{n} - 1 \\ \end{align*}\]

Putting it together

Our total number of expected steps is the sum of the expected random button presses, and the expected number of forward button presses. These are both functions of the closeness threshold \(n\), so once we have the formula, well want to find the \(n\) that minimizes the number of steps.

\[\begin{align*} E[S] = & E[R] + E[F] \\ = & \frac{N}{n} - 1 + \frac{1}{2}(n - 1) \\ = & \frac{N}{n} + \frac{n}{2} + \frac{1}{2} \\ \end{align*}\]

This is enough for us to plot the expected steps at each value of the closeness threshold \(n\). Here, were first plotting all values, and then limiting it to just those values close to the minimum. From here, we can eyeball the minimum at \(n = 14\).

At our minimizing threshold, we get a pretty balanced mix of expected random and forward steps:

## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   metric        value
##   <chr>         <dbl>
## 1 Random steps   6.14
## 2 Forward steps  6.5 
## 3 Steps         12.6

Here we can see how that balance plays out for each possible value of the closeness threshold \(n\). Not unexpectedly, when we give a crazy large threshold for closeness, the next buttons dominate, and thats a linear trend.

Rule of thumb

What do we do if our number of songs isnt \(N = 100\), but some other value? We can use a little calc on our expected steps function to differentiate and find the minimum of expected steps as a function of that value \(N\).

\[\begin{align*} E[S] = & \frac{N}{n} - 1 + \frac{1}{2}(n - 1) \\ \frac{d}{dn}E[S] = & \frac{-N}{n^2} + 0 + \frac{1}{2} \\ 0 = & \frac{-N}{n^2} + \frac{1}{2} \\ n^2 = & 2N \\ n = & \sqrt{2N} \\ \end{align*}\]

\[\begin{align*} = & \sqrt{2 \cdot 100} \\ = & 14.14 \\ \end{align*}\]

Does this hold up under trials?

Enough maths. Lets try doing a whole bunch of trials with different cutoffs, and see what we find.
